    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the shoe thing makes sense but it feels a bit too simple. i heard einstein called it 'spooky action at a distance' because it doesn't seem to follow normal physics. why exactly did he think it was so weird/spooky? like what is the actual mechanism that's breaking the rules?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, Einstein's \"spooky action at a distance\" refers to the peculiar nature of quantum entanglement, which seems to defy the very fabric of classical physics. Einstein, along with his colleagues Podolsky and Rosen, formulated a thought experiment known as the EPR paradox to challenge the completeness of quantum mechanics. They argued that if quantum mechanics were correct, it would imply that information could travel instantaneously between entangled particles, which seemed to violate the principle of locality. Locality is the idea that objects are only directly influenced by their immediate surroundings, not by distant events.\n\nEinstein found this unsettling because it suggested that the universe had a deeper level of interconnectedness that couldn't be explained by the classical laws of physics. In his view, there must be some hidden variables at play, which would preserve the classical notion of locality and causality. However, subsequent experiments, most notably those by John Bell and his theorem, have shown that quantum entanglement does indeed occur and that the predictions of quantum mechanics hold true, even when it comes to these \"spooky\" correlations.\n\nThe actual mechanism behind quantum entanglement is still a topic of much debate and research. One popular interpretation is the many-worlds interpretation, which suggests that",
      "source": "target",
