      "content": "The many-worlds interpretation (MWI) of quantum mechanics posits that every quantum event is a branching point where the universe splits into multiple, non-communicating parallel universes, or \"worlds.\" According to this interpretation, when two particles become entangled, their states are not just correlated; they are actually connected across all possible outcomes of their interactions. So, when a measurement is made on one particle, the universe splits into two branches: one where the measurement outcome is observed, and another where it is not.\n\nIn the branch where the measurement outcome is observed, the entangled particle's state is determined, and the other particle, no matter how far away, instantaneously assumes the corresponding state. This doesn't mean that information travels faster than light; rather, both outcomes exist simultaneously in separate branches of the universe. The MWI suggests that each branch represents a different version of reality, and the entangled particles remain connected across these branches.\n\nThis interpretation avoids the need for \"spooky action at a distance\" because there's no instantaneous communication between particles; instead, the entire universe is constantly splitting into different versions, each with its own set of outcomes. The entangled particles are just two of the many versions that exist in parallel universes",
